<div id="review_730435098" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/730435098" />
    <a title="Claire Walker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15316468-claire-walker"><img alt="Claire Walker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1355050291p2/15316468.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/730435098?book_show_action=true">Sep 29, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Claire Walker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Claire Walker" href="/user/show/15316468-claire-walker">Claire Walker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15316468-claire-walker?shelf=favourites-2013">favourites-2013</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer730435098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12167479373958805338">You can read more of my reviews at <a href='http://therabidbookworm.com' rel='nofollow noopener'>the rabid bookworm</a><br/><br/>To say that I am a fan of this series is a mild understatement. I first picked up infected back in 2009 when I’d been set on some awful training course for 3 days and was stuck in a bland hotel with no hope of entertainment at night.<br/><br/>Knowing I was in for 3 nights of utter boredom I went to a bookshop near the hotel to grab something to read. The cover of infected intrigued me, so I bought it thinking I’ll read a few chapters before bed.. this d</span>
  <span id="freeText12167479373958805338" style="display:none">You can read more of my reviews at <a href="http://therabidbookworm.com" rel="nofollow noopener">the rabid bookworm</a><br /><br />To say that I am a fan of this series is a mild understatement. I first picked up infected back in 2009 when I’d been set on some awful training course for 3 days and was stuck in a bland hotel with no hope of entertainment at night.<br /><br />Knowing I was in for 3 nights of utter boredom I went to a bookshop near the hotel to grab something to read. The cover of infected intrigued me, so I bought it thinking I’ll read a few chapters before bed.. this did not happen, instead I stayed up until 4am, horrified and wanting to claw my own skin off but desperate to finish the book. I was now a fan of Scott Sigler!<br /><br />When I got an ARC of Pandemic you have no idea of the fangirl squeals of delight that came from me, it was quite shameful – but anyway, on with the review!<br /><br />I've tried to keep this review spoiler free but don't read it if you've not read infected or contagious - there are spoilers for those two books.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[We begin 5 years after the death of Dew Phillips and ‘Scary’ Perry Dawsey, half of the States hate Margaret Montoya blaming her for the nuking of Detroit, the other half hail her a saviour. She’s become a reclusive shut in, unable to function with the guilt and the hatred thrown her way, not even Clarence Otto can get through to her. Margaret sits at her desk all day long reading the blog posts aimed at her and looking at pictures of Dew, Perry and Amos.<br /><br />For the last 5 years the government has been scouring the bottom of Lake Michigan, recovering parts of the Orbital but nothing of importance has yet to be found. Remaining undiscovered at the bottom of the lake is a soda can size object.. the humans don’t know that before it was brought down the orbital managed to alter the spores once again and this time success seems guaranteed.<br /><br />Pandemic has all of the high speed, thrilling aspects of it’s predecessors and it also feels bigger because the infection finally makes it out of the States but I felt that there was something missing. Specifically there was a very large Perry Dawsey and Dew Phillips size hole, no matter how much Margaret and Clarence took centre stage, they just couldn’t carry the book the way our dearly departed heroes did.<br /><br />That aside though, pandemic is fabulous! We’re led right through the beginning stage of the infection, bite our knuckles as bad decisions are made and the conclusion – oh my god you will not see it coming, it is a total mindfuck!<br /><br />So much as I miss old Perry &amp; Dew, Pandemic is absolutely not to be missed by any Sigler fans and I’d recommend it to anyone! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="12167479373958805338" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


